<Prose
  title="What is Geomancy?"
  description="An introduction to geomancy, the great divinatory art of medieval and Renaissance Europe: its history, its sixteen figures, and how it differs from astrology."
  crumbs={[{ name: 'What is Geomancy?' }]}
  kicker="Introduction"
  jsonLd={[{ '@type': 'Article', headline: 'What is Geomancy?' }]}
>
  <p>
    Geomancy (“divination by earth”) answers questions by figures of points. Sixteen lines of
    points are made at hazard; from their odd or even remainders are built four figures, the
    <em>Mothers</em>, and from these the whole chart is derived by rule: Daughters, Nieces,
    Witnesses, and the Judge that resolves the question. The figures are read in the twelve houses
    of heaven, after the manner of astrology, but no ephemeris, table or instrument is needed, only
    pen, paper, and an earnest question.
  </p>
  <p>Agrippa's treatise opens with as good a definition as any:</p>
  <Quote id="agrippa/general/casting-mothers" compact />
  <p>
    The art reached Europe in the twelfth century through Latin translations from Arabic,
    <em>ʿilm al-raml</em>, “the science of the sand,” and the same sixteen figures are cast to
    this day in West African and Malagasy divination. In Europe it became the most practised of
    all divinatory arts after astrology itself, taught by scholastic authorities like Pietro
    d'Abano and printed in great manuals through the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries: Cattan's
    <em>Geomancie</em>, translated into English in 1591, and John Heydon's vast
    <em>Theomagia</em> of 1663. Robert Turner's 1655 translation of the <em>Fourth Book of Occult
    Philosophy</em> carried two treatises (the <em>Of Geomancy</em> attributed to Agrippa and the
    medieval <em>Astronomical Geomancy</em> of Gerard of Cremona) that remain the most read
    English texts of the art.
  </p>
  <p>
    The geomancers called their art the <em>daughter of astrology</em>: it borrows the twelve
    houses, the planets and signs, aspects, and essential dignities; but where astrology computes
    the actual heavens, geomancy raises its “heaven” from the points themselves. As the historical
    authors insist, the virtue of the art lies not in the marks on the paper but in the motion of
    the soul that makes them.
  </p>
